    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, that looks pretty good. maybe make it a little more personal though? the candidate specifically mentioned how much they liked our company culture and how they were really excited about our specific tech stack. i don't want it to sound like a boilerplate robot sent it, but i still need to keep it professional. can you tweak it to acknowledge their enthusiasm a bit more?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a smart move; acknowledging their specific interest makes a huge difference. You want to show you *heard* them, not just that you *read* them. I've tweaked the draft to weave in that cultural and tech stack appreciation. It sounds warmer, but still maintains that necessary professional distance.\n\nHere is the revised version:\n\n***\n\n**Subject: Update on the Senior Developer Role at [Company Name]**\n\nDear [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you again for investing so much time in the interview process for the Senior Developer role. We genuinely enjoyed our conversations, and I especially appreciated hearing how excited you were about our company culture and the specific tech stack we use here. It’s clear you did your homework, and that level of enthusiasm is something we always value.\n\nThe final decision was incredibly tough, as your technical skills are truly top-tier. We have, however, decided to move forward with another candidate whose background was a slightly closer match for the immediate, niche requirements of our current sprint. Please know this decision was not a reflection of your talent—you are a very capable developer, and we were genuinely impressed.\n\nWe wish you the absolute best in finding a role where you can thrive,",
      "source": "target",
